uiparam.name: Enable DDR
uiparam.desc: Enable DDR Controller of Zynq PS

uiparam.name: Memory Type
uiparam.desc: Type of memory interface. Refer to UG585 Zynq Technical Reference Manual (TRM) for a detailed list of supported memory controllers.

uiparam.name: Memory Part
uiparam.desc: Memory component part number. For unlisted parts choose "Custom". This will enable user input in the "Memory Part Configuration" section.

uiparam.name: Effective DRAM Bus Width
uiparam.desc: Data width of DDR interface, not including ECC data width. Refer to UG585 for a detailed list of supported DDR data widths.

uiparam.name: ECC
uiparam.desc: Enables error correction code support. ECC is supported only for an effective data width of 16 bits.

uiparam.name: Burst Length
uiparam.desc: Minimum number of data beats the controller should use when communicating with the DDR component.

uiparam.name: Internal Vref
uiparam.desc: Enables internal voltage reference source. Disable to use external Vref pins as voltage reference.

uiparam.name: DDR
uiparam.desc: Memory clock period. The allowed freq range is

uiparam.name: Operating Temperature (C)
uiparam.desc: Intended operating temperature range. Controls the DDR refresh interval.

uiparam.name: DRAM Device Capacity
uiparam.desc: Storage capacity of individual DRAM components.

uiparam.name: Speed Bin
uiparam.desc: Speed bin of the individual DRAM components.

uiparam.name: CAS Latency (cycles)
uiparam.desc: Column Access Strobe (CAS) latency in memory clock cycles. It refers to the amount of time it takes for data to appear on the pins of the memory module

uiparam.name: CAS Write Latency (cycles)
uiparam.desc: CAS write latency setting in memory clock cycles.

uiparam.name: RAS to CAS Delay (cycles)
uiparam.desc: tRCD. Row address to column address delay time. It is the time required between the memory controller asserting a row address strobe (RAS), and then asserting the column address strobe (CAS)

uiparam.name: Precharge Time
uiparam.desc: tRP. Precharge Time is the number of clock cycles needed to terminate access to an open row of memory and open access to the next row.

uiparam.name: tRASmin (ns)
uiparam.desc: Minimum number of memory clock cycles required between an Active and Precharge command

uiparam.name: tFAW (ns)
uiparam.desc: Determines the number of activates that can be performed within a certain window of time.

uiparam.name: Additive Latency (ns)
uiparam.desc: Additive Latency (ns). Increases the efficiency of the command and data bus for sustainable bandwidths

uiparam.name: DQS0
uiparam.desc: DQS to Clock delay [0] (ns). The DQS path delay subtracted from the clock path delay.

uiparam.name: DQS1
uiparam.desc: DQS to Clock delay [1] (ns). The DQS path delay subtracted from the clock path delay.

uiparam.name: DQS2
uiparam.desc: DQS to Clock delay [2] (ns). The DQS path delay subtracted from the clock path delay.

uiparam.name: DQS3
uiparam.desc: DQS to Clock delay [3] (ns). The DQS path delay subtracted from the clock path delay.

uiparam.name: Write leveling
uiparam.desc: Enables Write Leveling calibration, which adjusts write DQS relative to the DDR clock.

uiparam.name: Read gate
uiparam.desc: Enables Read Gate calibration, which adjusts valid RD DQS window.

uiparam.name: Read data eye
uiparam.desc: Enables Read Data Eye calibration, which adjusts the read DQS to the center of read DQ.

uiparam.name: DQ[7:0]
uiparam.desc: Board delay [0] (ns). The midpoint of data (DDR_DQ, DDR_DM) trace delays averaged with the midpoint of clock (DDR_CK, DR_CK_N) trace delays for byte lane 0.

uiparam.name: DQ[15:8]
uiparam.desc: Board delay [1] (ns). The midpoint of data (DDR_DQ, DDR_DM) trace delays averaged with the midpoint of clock (DDR_CK, DR_CK_N) trace delays for byte lane 1.

uiparam.name: DQ[23:16]
uiparam.desc: Board delay [2] (ns). The midpoint of data (DDR_DQ, DDR_DM) trace delays averaged with the midpoint of clock (DDR_CK, DR_CK_N) trace delays for byte lane 2.

uiparam.name: DQ[31:24]
uiparam.desc: Board delay [3] (ns). The midpoint of data (DDR_DQ, DDR_DM) trace delays averaged with the midpoint of clock (DDR_CK, DR_CK_N) trace delays for byte lane 3.

uiparam.name: DDR Write Port 0-Priority (L2 Cache)
uiparam.desc: The write priority of DDR port 0. This sets an initial value for an aging down-counter (High = 0x4, Medium = 0x200, and Low = 0x3ff). At any instant, a lower aging counter value takes priority over a higher one

uiparam.name: DDR Write Port 1-Priority (Switch)
uiparam.desc: The write priority of DDR port 1. This sets an initial value for an aging down-counter (High = 0x4, Medium = 0x200, and Low = 0x3ff). At any instant, a lower aging counter value takes priority over a higher one

uiparam.name: DDR Write Port 2-Priority (HP2/HP3)
uiparam.desc: The write priority of DDR port 2. This sets an initial value for an aging down-counter (High = 0x4, Medium = 0x200, and Low = 0x3ff). At any instant, a lower aging counter value takes priority over a higher one

uiparam.name: DDR Write Port 3-Priority (HP0/HP1)
uiparam.desc: The write priority of DDR port 3. This sets an initial value for an aging down-counter (High = 0x4, Medium = 0x200, and Low = 0x3ff). At any instant, a lower aging counter value takes priority over a higher one

uiparam.name: DDR Read Port 0-Priority (L2 Cache)
uiparam.desc: The read priority of DDR port 0. This sets an initial value for an aging down-counter (High = 0x0, Medium = 0x200, and Low = 0x3ff). At any instant, a lower aging counter value takes priority over a higher one

uiparam.name: DDR Read Port 1-Priority (Switch)
uiparam.desc: The read priority of DDR port 1. This sets an initial value for an aging down-counter (High = 0x0, Medium = 0x200, and Low = 0x3ff). At any instant, a lower aging counter value takes priority over a higher one

uiparam.name: DDR Read Port 2-Priority (HP2/HP3)
uiparam.desc: The read priority of DDR port 2. This sets an initial value for an aging down-counter (High = 0x0, Medium = 0x200, and Low = 0x3ff). At any instant, a lower aging counter value takes priority over a higher one

uiparam.name: DDR Read Port 3-Priority (HP0/HP1)
uiparam.desc: The read priority of DDR port 3. This sets an initial value for an aging down-counter (High = 0x0, Medium = 0x200, and Low = 0x3ff). At any instant, a lower aging counter value takes priority over a higher one

uiparam.name: DDR Port 0-Enable HPR
uiparam.desc: Enables the usage of high priority reads on DDR port 0. This port is used by the CPUs and the ACP via the L2 Cache

uiparam.name: DDR Port 1-Enable HPR
uiparam.desc: Enables the usage of high priority reads on DDR port 1. This port is used by other masters via the central interconnect

uiparam.name: DDR Port 2-Enable HPR
uiparam.desc: Enables the usage of high priority reads on DDR port 2. This port is used by HP2 and HP3

uiparam.name: DDR Port 3-Enable HPR
uiparam.desc: Enables the usage of high priority reads on DDR port 3. This port is used by HP0 and HP1

uiparam.name: HPR/LPR Queue Partitioning
uiparam.desc: Indicates the desired partitioning for high and low priority reads in the queue. Note that the queue has a depth of 32 read requests

uiparam.name: LPR to Critical Priority Level
uiparam.desc: The number of clocks that the LPR queue can be starved before it goes critical. Unit: 32 DDR clock cycles. This value sets the DDR LPR_reg register. Valid values are between 0 and 2047

uiparam.name: HPR to Critical Priority Level
uiparam.desc: The number of clocks that the HPR queue can be starved before it goes critical. Unit: 32 DDR clock cycles. This value sets the DDR HPR_reg register. Valid values are between 0 and 2047

uiparam.name: Write to Critical Priority Level
uiparam.desc: Write to Critical Priority Level The number of clocks that the write queue can be starved before it goes critical. Unit: 32 DDR clock cycles. This value sets the DDR WR_reg register. Valid values are between 0 and 2047
